35 PART III. PRACTICE OF FUNERAL SERVICE/BOARD CHANGES
36 SECTION 3.1. G.S. 90-210.18A reads as rewritten:
37 "§ 90-210.18A. Board of Funeral Service created; qualifications; vacancies; removal.
38 (a) The General Assembly declares that the practice of funeral service affects the public
39 health, safety, and welfare and is subject to regulation and control in the public interest. The
40 public interest requires that only qualified persons be permitted to practice funeral service in
41 North Carolina and that the profession merit the confidence of the public. This Article shall be
42 liberally construed to accomplish these ends.
43 (b) The North Carolina Board of Funeral Service is created and shall regulate the practice
44 of funeral service in this State. The Board shall have nine members as follows:
45 (1) Four Three members appointed by the Governor from nominees
46 recommended by the North Carolina Funeral Directors Association, Inc.
47 These members shall be persons licensed under this Article.
48 (2) Two Three members appointed by the Governor from nominees
49 recommended by the Funeral Directors & Morticians Association of North
50 Carolina, Inc. These members shall be persons licensed under this Article.
House Bill 1003-Third Edition Page 17

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (3) One member appointed by the Governor who is licensed under this Article
2 and who is not affiliated with any funeral service trade association.
3 (4) One member appointed by the General Assembly, upon the recommendation
4 of the President Pro Tempore of the Senate. This member shall be a person
5 who is not licensed under this Article or employed by a person who is licensed
6 under this Article.
7 (5) One member appointed by the General Assembly, upon the recommendation
8 of the Speaker of the House of Representatives. This member shall be a person
9 who is not licensed under this Article or employed by a person who is licensed
10 under this Article.
11 Members of the Board shall serve staggered three-year terms, ending on December 31 of the
12 last year of the term or when a successor has been duly appointed, whichever is later. No member
13 may serve more than two complete consecutive terms.
