1 (a) After the death of a preneed funeral contract beneficiary and full performance of the
2 preneed funeral contract by the preneed licensee, the performing preneed licensee shall promptly
3 complete a certificate of performance and present it to the financial institution that holds funds
4 in trust under G.S. 90-210.61(a)(1) or to the insurance company that issued a preneed insurance
5 policy pursuant to G.S. 90-210.61(a)(3). Upon receipt of the certificate of performance or similar
6 claim form, the financial institution shall pay the trust funds to the contracting performing
7 preneed licensee and the insurance company shall pay the insurance proceeds according to the
8 terms of the policy. Within 10 days after receiving payment, the performing preneed licensee
9 shall file a copy of the certificate of performance or other claim form to the Board.
10 (b) Unless otherwise specified in the preneed funeral contract, the preneed licensee shall
11 have no obligation to deliver merchandise or perform any services for which payment in full has
12 not yet been deposited with a financial institution or that will not be provided by the proceeds of
13 a prearrangement insurance policy. Any such amounts received which do not constitute payment
14 in full shall be refunded to the estate of the deceased preneed funeral contract beneficiary or
15 credited against the cost of merchandise or services contracted for by a representative of the
16 deceased. Any balance remaining after payment for the merchandise and services as set forth in
17 the preneed funeral contract shall be paid to the estate of the preneed funeral contract beneficiary
18 or the prearrangement insurance policy beneficiary named to receive any such balance. Provided,
19 however, unless the parties agree to the contrary, there shall be no refund to the estate of the
20 preneed funeral contract beneficiary of an inflation-proof preneed funeral contract except as
21 required by G.S. 90-210.63A(c).
22 (c) In the event that any person other than the contracting preneed licensee performs any
23 funeral service or provides any merchandise as a result of the death of the preneed funeral
24 contract beneficiary, the financial institution shall pay the trust funds to the contracting
25 performing preneed licensee and the insurance company shall pay the insurance proceeds
26 according to the terms of the policy. The preneed licensee shall, subject to the provisions of
27 G.S. 90-210.65(d), immediately pay the monies so received to the other provider.The performing
28 preneed licensee shall provide the contracting preneed licensee with a copy of the certificate of
29 performance prepared for the decedent contemporaneously upon submission to the Board on or
30 before 10 days of payment.
31 (d) When the balance of a preneed funeral fund is one thousand dollars ($1,000) or less
32 and is payable to the estate of a deceased preneed funeral contract beneficiary and there has been
33 no representative of the estate appointed, the balance due may be paid directly to a beneficiary
34 or to the beneficiaries of the estate. If the balance of a preneed funeral fund exceeds one thousand
35 dollars ($1,000) or is not payable to the estate, the balance must be paid into the office of the
36 clerk of superior court in the county where probate proceedings could be filed for the deceased
37 preneed funeral contract beneficiary.
38 (e) Upon For trust funded preneed funeral contracts, upon the fulfillment of a preneed
39 contract, all of the following items shall be completed within 30 days:
40 (1) The contracting performing preneed licensee must submit a certificate of
41 performance or similar claim form to the financial institution holding the
42 preneed trust funds and close the preneed account.
43 (2) The proceeds of this trust account shall be distributed according to the terms
44 of the preneed contract.
45 (3) A completed copy of the certificate of performance or similar claim form
46 evidencing the final disposition of any financial institution preneed trust
47 account funds must be filed with the Board by the contracting performing
48 licensee."
49 SECTION 4.6. G.S. 90-210.67 reads as rewritten:
50 "§ 90-210.67. Application for license.
51 …
Page 46 House Bill 1003-Third Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (b) An application for a preneed funeral establishment license shall be accompanied by a
2 nonrefundable application fee of not more than four hundred dollars ($400.00). The Board shall
3 set the amounts of the application fees and renewal fees, by rule.
4 If the license is granted, the application fee shall be applied to the annual license fee for the
5 first year or part thereof. Upon receipt of the application and payment of the application fee, the
6 Board shall issue a renewable preneed funeral establishment license unless it determines that the
7 applicant has violated any provision of G.S. 90-210.69(c) or has made false statements or
8 representations in the application, or is insolvent, or has conducted or is about to conduct, its
9 business in a fraudulent manner, or is not duly authorized to transact business in this State. The
10 license shall expire on December 31 and each preneed funeral establishment licensee shall pay
11 annually to the Board on or before that date a license renewal fee of not more than two hundred
12 fifty dollars ($250.00). On or after After February 1, a license may be renewed by paying a late
13 fee of not more than one hundred dollars ($100.00) in addition to the annual renewal fee. Preneed
14 funeral establishment permits that remain expired six months or more cannot be renewed and
15 establishments must reapply for licensure pursuant to this subsection.
16 If, after January 1, 2008, a funeral establishment receiving a new preneed establishment
17 license or if a preneed establishment license has lapsed or has been terminated for any reason,
18 other than for failure to timely renew the license, the funeral establishment shall obtain a surety
19 bond in an amount not less than fifty thousand dollars ($50,000) for a period of at least two years;
20 provided, however, that the Board, in its discretion, may require the term of the surety bond to
21 be for five years. However, upon demonstrating to the satisfaction of the Board that the funeral
22 establishment is solvent, the Board may reduce the bond term to a period of no less than one year
23 from the date the original license is issued. The funeral establishment may (i) purchase the bond
24 from any company authorized by law to sell bonds in this State or (ii) deposit fifty thousand
25 dollars ($50,000) with the clerk of superior court in the county where the preneed funeral
26 establishment maintains its facility that is licensed or has submitted an application for licensure
27 to the Board. The Board may extend the bonding requirement beyond a period of five years in
28 the event there is a claim paid from the bond.
29 (c) An application for a preneed sales license shall be accompanied by a nonrefundable
30 application fee of not more than fifty dollars ($50.00). The Board shall set the amounts of the
31 application fees and renewal fees by rule, but the fees shall not exceed fifty dollars ($50.00). If
32 the license is granted, the application fee shall be applied to the annual license fee for the first
33 year or part thereof. Upon receipt of the application and payment of the application fee, the Board
34 shall issue a renewable preneed sales license provided the applicant has met the qualifications to
35 engage in preneed funeral planning as established by the Board unless it determines that the
36 applicant has violated any provision of G.S. 90-210.69(c). The license shall expire on December
37 31 and each preneed sales licensee shall pay annually to the Board on or before that date a license
38 renewal fee of not more than fifty dollars ($50.00). On or after After February 1, a license may
39 be renewed by paying a late fee of not more than twenty-five dollars ($25.00) in addition to the
40 annual renewal fee.
41 …."
42 SECTION 4.7. G.S. 90-210.68 reads as rewritten:
43 "§ 90-210.68. Licensee's books and records; notice of transfers, assignments and
44 terminations.
45 …
46 (a1) On or before March 31, 31 of each year, each preneed licensee shall prepare and
47 submit an annual report on its preneed funeral contract sales and during the previous calendar
48 year, to include the total number, status, and type of each preneed contract for which the preneed
49 licensee serves as trustee, the total year-end balance of each contract, and the status of each
50 preneed contract. The preneed licensee shall submit the report to the Board in a manner and form
51 prescribed by the Board.
House Bill 1003-Third Edition Page 47

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 …
2 (c) If any preneed licensee transfers or assigns its assets or stock to a successor funeral
3 establishment or terminates its business as a funeral establishment, the preneed licensee and
4 assignee shall notify the Board at least 30 days prior to the effective date of the transfer,
5 assignment or termination: provided, however, the successor funeral establishment must be a
6 preneed licensee in good standing with the Board or shall be required to apply for and be granted
7 such license by the Board before accepting any preneed funeral contracts, whether funded by
8 trust deposits or preneed insurance policies. Provided further, a successor funeral establishment
9 shall be liable to the preneed funeral contract purchasers for the amount of contract payments
10 retained by the assigning or transferring funeral home pursuant to G.S. 90-210.61(a)(2).
11 (d) Financial institutions that accept preneed funeral trust funds and insurance companies
12 that issue or assign insurance policies that are used to fund preneed funeral contracts shall, upon
13 request by the Board or its inspectors or examiners, disclose any information regarding preneed
14 funeral trust accounts held or any insurance policies used to fund a preneed funeral contract.and,
15 for any insurance policy that names a funeral establishment as an assignee or beneficiary, the
16 issuing or underwriting insurance company shall, upon request by the Board or its inspectors,
17 disclose any information regarding the preneed funeral trust accounts or any insurance policy
18 that names a funeral establishment as an assignee or beneficiary.
19 Financial institutions that accept preneed funeral trust funds and insurance companies that
20 issue or assign insurance policy proceeds or designate a preneed funeral establishment as a policy
21 beneficiary or owner and, for any insurance policy that names a funeral establishment as an
22 assignee or beneficiary, the issuing or underwriting insurance company shall also forward an the
23 account balance or policy status and current death benefit to the contracting preneed funeral
24 establishment or the funeral establishment named as an assignee or beneficiary at the end of each
25 calendar year.
26 (d1) When a preneed funeral establishment license lapses or is terminated for any reason,
27 the preneed licensee shall immediately divest of all the unperformed preneed funeral contracts
28 and shall transfer them and any amounts retained under G.S. 90-210.61(a)(2) to another a
29 successor preneed funeral establishment licensee in good standing with the Board pursuant to the
30 procedures of subsection (e) of this section. The contracting and the successor preneed funeral
31 establishments shall notify the Board at least 30 days prior to such transfer. Within 30 days
32 following the transfer, the contracting and successor preneed funeral establishments shall provide
33 notice of the transfer to each preneed contract purchaser and to the financial institution housing
34 the preneed funeral trust funds or the issuing or underwriting insurance company for the
35 contracts.
36 (e) In the event that any preneed licensee is unable or unwilling or is for any reason
37 relieved of its responsibility to perform as trustee or to perform any preneed funeral contract, the
38 Board shall order the contract and any amounts retained pursuant to G.S. 90-210.61(a)(2) to be
39 assigned to a substitute preneed licensee provided that neither the substitute preneed licensee or
40 preneed contract purchaser, or after the death of the preneed contract purchaser, the preneed
41 contract beneficiary or his or her legal representative, shall be obligated to perform the agreement
42 without executing a new preneed funeral contract. Any lapse or transfer of a preneed contract
43 pursuant to this section shall not be grounds to revoke an irrevocable preneed funeral contract.
44 (f) The substitute preneed licensee under subsections (d1) and (e) of this section shall be
45 liable to the preneed funeral contract purchasers for the amount of contract payments that had
46 been retained by, and that the substitute preneed licensee has received from, the assigning
47 preneed licensee."
48 SECTION 4.8. G.S. 90-210.69 reads as rewritten:
49 "§ 90-210.69. Rulemaking; enforcement of Article; judicial review; determination of
50 penalty amount.
Page 48 House Bill 1003-Third Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (a) The Board is authorized to adopt rules for the carrying out and enforcement of the
2 provisions of this Article. The Board may perform such other acts and exercise such other powers
3 and duties as are authorized by this Article and by Article 13A of this Chapter to carry out its
4 powers and duties.
5 (b) The Board may administer oaths and issue subpoenas requiring the attendance of
6 persons and the production of papers and records in any investigation conducted by it. Members
7 of the Board's staff or the sheriff or other appropriate official of any county of this State shall
8 serve all notices, subpoenas and other papers given to them by the Board for service in the same
9 manner as process issued by any court of record. Any person who does not obey a subpoena
10 issued by the Board shall be guilty of a misdemeanor and, upon conviction thereof, shall be fined
11 or imprisoned in the discretion of the court.
12 (b1) Upon determining that it is necessary for the protection of the interest of a preneed
13 contract purchaser or beneficiary, the Board may issue a written order to direct that the preneed
14 funds of any preneed licensee on deposit in any institution operating under this Article be frozen
15 and not paid out by such legal entity. Any legal entity freezing the preneed funds pursuant to the
16 directive of the Board shall not be liable for freezing an account pursuant to an order of the Board.
17 (c) The Board may place on probation, refuse to issue or renew, suspend, or revoke a
18 preneed license when an owner, partner, manager, member, operator, officer, or preneed
19 salesperson of the preneed funeral licensee violates any provision of this Article or any rules
20 adopted by the Board, or when any agent or employee of the preneed funeral establishment, with
21 the consent of any person, firm, or corporation operating the funeral establishment, violates any
22 of these provisions, rules, or regulations. In accordance with the provisions of Chapter 150B of
23 the General Statutes, if the Board finds that a licensee, an applicant for a license or an applicant
24 for license renewal is guilty of one or more of the following, the Board may refuse to issue or
25 renew a license or may suspend or revoke a license or place the holder thereof on probation upon
26 conditions set by the Board, with revocation upon failure to comply with the conditions:
27 (1) Offering to engage or engaging in activities for which a license is required
28 under this Article but without having obtained such a license.
29 (2) Aiding or abetting an unlicensed person, firm, partnership, association,
30 corporation or other entity to offer to engage or engage in such activities.
31 (3) A crime involving fraud or moral turpitude by conviction thereof.Conviction
32 of, or plea of guilty or nolo contendere to, a felony or a misdemeanor that
33 indicates that the individual is unfit or incompetent to engage in preneed
34 funeral service or that the individual has deceived or defrauded the public.
35 (4) Fraud or misrepresentation in obtaining or receiving a license in preneed
36 funeral planning or in the operation of a licensee's business.
37 (5) False or misleading advertising.
38 (6) Violating or cooperating with others to violate any provision of this Article or
39 Article 13A, 13E, or 13F of this Chapter, the rules and regulations of the
40 Board, or the standards set forth in Funeral Industry Practices, 16 C.F.R. 453
41 (1984), as amended from time to time.
42 (7) Denial, suspension, or revocation of an occupational or business license by
43 another jurisdiction.
44 (8) Failure to refund any insurance proceeds received as consideration in excess
45 of the funeral contract purchase price within 30 days of receipt; provided,
46 however, that this provision shall not be construed to include interest or
47 growth on funds paid toward funeral goods and services to be provided
48 pursuant to an inflation-proof preneed contract.
49 (9) Failure to provide, within a reasonable time, either the goods and services
50 contracted for or a refund for the price of goods and services paid but not
51 fulfilled.
House Bill 1003-Third Edition Page 49

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (10) Violation of G.S. 58-58-97.
2 (11) Failure to respond to the Board's inquiries in a reasonable manner or time
3 regarding any matter affecting the individual's performance of preneed funeral
4 services.
5 Revocation of a funeral establishment permit granted pursuant to G.S. 90-210.25(d)(2) shall
6 result in the automatic revocation of the firm's preneed funeral establishment permit by operation
7 of law. Active suspension of a funeral establishment permit granted pursuant to
8 G.S. 90-210.25(d)(2) shall result in the automatic active suspension of the firm's preneed funeral
9 establishment permit for the same length of time by operation of law. In any case in which the
10 Board is authorized to take any of the actions permitted under this subsection, the Board may
11 instead accept an offer in compromise of the charges whereby the accused shall pay to the Board
12 a penalty of not more than five thousand dollars ($5,000). In any case in which the Board is
13 entitled to place a licensee on a term of probation, the Board may also impose a penalty of not
14 more than five thousand dollars ($5,000) in conjunction with such probation. The Board may
15 determine the length and conditions of any period of probation, revocation, suspension, or refusal
16 to issue or renew a license.
17 (d) Any proceedings pertaining to or actions against a funeral establishment under this
18 Article may be in addition to any proceedings or actions permitted by G.S. 90-210.25(d)(4). Any
19 proceedings pertaining to or actions against a person licensed for funeral directing or funeral
20 service may be in addition to any proceedings or actions permitted by G.S. 90-210.25 (e)(1) and
21 (2).
22 (e) Judicial review shall be pursuant to Article 4 of Chapter 150B of the General Statutes.
23 (f) In determining the amount of any penalty imposed or assessed under Article 13 of
24 Chapter 90 of the General Statutes, the Board shall consider:
25 (1) The degree and extent of harm to the public health, safety, and welfare, or to
26 property, or the potential for harm.
27 (2) The duration and gravity of the violation.
28 (3) Whether the violation was committed willfully or intentionally or reflects a
29 continuing pattern.
30 (4) Whether the violation involved elements of fraud or deception either to the
31 public or to the Board, or both.
32 (5) The violator's prior disciplinary record with the Board.
33 (6) Whether and the extent to which the violator profited by the violation."
34 SECTION 4.9. G.S. 90-210.70 reads as rewritten:
35 "§ 90-210.70. Penalties.
36 …
37 (e) Whenever it shall appear to the Board that any person, firm, or corporation has
38 violated, threatens to violate, or is violating any provisions of this Article, the Board may apply
39 to the courts of the State for a restraining order and injunction to restrain these practices. If upon
40 application the court finds that any provision of this Article is being violated, or a violation is
41 threatened, the court shall issue an order restraining and enjoining the violations, and this relief
42 may be granted regardless of whether criminal prosecution is instituted under the provisions of
43 this subsection. The venue for actions brought under this subsection shall be the superior court
44 of (i) any county in which the acts are alleged to have been committed or in committed, (ii) the
45 county where the defendant in the action resides.resides, or (iii) Wake County."
